story.title: Falco - Episode 7
story.storyDescription: Libby Dixon is missing. Will Agent Falco crack the case?
story.creator: web-uploader
story.prePaywallNotification: WHAT?! Libby Dixon was PREGNANT? 🤰😬 Who is the father? Tap back into Hooked to find out.
story.postPaywallNotification: Even Libby’s mom admits that Libby was scared of her father…could he have something to do with her disappearance? 😬😬 Tap back into Hooked to find out.

messages.text: Investigation: Day 7
The following is a transcript of an interview between Agent Falco, Lynette Dixon, and Darrence Dixon, recorded June 26, 4:19 PM.
Thanks for coming in again, Mr. and Mrs. Dixon.
I can assure you we’re doing all we can to find your daughter.
Is this about her computer?
Did you find something?
Damn it, I should’ve checked it sooner.
I completely forgot in all the commotion.
I should’ve checked the tracker — I never really looked.
She didn’t seem to use her computer all that much.
Well, she did use it prior to her disappearance.
I know this isn’t an easy question, but I have to ask.
Is it possible that your daughter was sexually active?
Absolutely not.
Premarital sex is a sin — she knows that.
She’s a good girl, detective.
Wait, what is this about?
Tell us what you found on the computer.
Libby had been searching the Internet for information about pregnancy.
Pregnancy?
She must have been doing a project for school.
She was just doing research for health class.
You can ask her friend, Rachel — they were working on an anatomy project together.
But these searches were dated early to mid-June—
The school year ended in May.
Our daughter was not sexually active, Agent Falco.
Darrence bangs his fist onto the table, startling Lynette.
I won’t allow you to tarnish her reputation with your baseless accusations.
I accessed her deleted text messages.
She didn’t want you to know she was seeing someone, sir.
I don’t appreciate this line of questioning, detective. I’m done here.
Darrence, wait.
Darrence storms out of the interview room as Lynette dissolves into sobs.
Please, Miss Falco.
Please help us find her.
I’m doing all I can, Mrs. Dixon, but I need your cooperation.
Do I have permission to access Libby’s medical records?
To see if she’s pregnant?
To see if I can get to the bottom of this whole thing.
Of course, yes — whatever you need.
Libby had also searched the Internet for “legal age for abortion.”
Could she have been afraid of Darrence’s reaction if she were pregnant?
Libby couldn’t be pregnant, detective—
And even if she were, she’d never consider abortion. She’s very pro-life—
We all are.
Darrence seems pretty upset about a possible pregnancy.
Let’s say he found something out before her disappearance…
Could he have harmed your daughter?
Absolutely not.
Lynette composes herself and shakes her head in defense of her husband.
He doesn’t believe in violence.
Blessed are the peacemakers, for they shall be called sons of God.
Does Darrence believe in corporal punishment, perhaps?
Spare the rod, spoil the child?
Libby’s too old for spankings, detective.
So how do you think your husband would’ve disciplined her?
You mean, if she were pregnant?
He would’ve kicked her out of the house.
His roof, his rules — but he never would’ve hurt her, Miss Falco.
And how would you describe Libby’s feelings toward your husband?
Do you think Libby’s afraid of her father?
I suppose she could’ve been scared of the repercussions…
But she would’ve told me if she were pregnant—
Confided in me.
And I would’ve helped her.
Behind your husband’s back?
Lynette looks down at the floor, dabbing at her eyes with a tissue.
If necessary, yes.
She’s my daughter, detective. I would’ve taken care of it.
The sin would be mine.
You would’ve gotten her an abortion?
I don’t know — but I could never let her sleep on the streets.
Could Libby have confided in her sister, Anna Mae?
Was Anna Mae too afraid to tell us something?
I don’t know.
They used to be so close before Anna Mae starting spending all her time with that boyfriend of hers.
Jimmy Fitz?
Yeah. To be honest, I was a little relieved when they broke up a few weeks ago.
Relieved?
Don’t tell her I said so, please.
She’s heartbroken over Jimmy.
But it’s not healthy to be so invested so young.
She’s only nineteen, you know.
Besides, Darrence wasn’t very fond of Jimmy.
How come?
He got a DUI when he was 18. Darrence didn’t like that.
I think Jimmy spent some time in jail before he moved to Cedar Creek.
Darrence said he’d forgiven Jimmy of his transgression, of course.
But I think Darrence still held it against him.
Can you think of any other reasons why your husband didn’t approve of their relationship?
Maybe because Jimmy’s broken up with Anna Mae so many times.
She’s had some ongoing issues because of him, you know.
But this time he seems to be gone for good.
So the girls drifted apart due to Anna Mae’s boy troubles?
Well, Libby had her own troubles with Duke, of course.
Of course.
Lynette blows her nose, and Agent Falco hands her another tissue from the box.
Is it okay if we take a look at Libby’s bedroom, Mrs. Dixon?
But Sheriff Simmons searched her room after we reported her missing.
I think it’s worth checking out one more time—
If there’s incriminating evidence against his son in Libby’s bedroom, Sheriff Simmons may have ignored it.
Okay, of course — whatever you need.
Deputy Decker will be by in the morning, then.
Get some rest tonight, okay?
I’ve got some other leads to follow up on.
Speaking of which, has Libby ever been to Newbury, Tennessee?
I don’t think so.
Have you ever heard of an Internet cafe called Wired?
No. Did you find something out about my daughter?
Lynette perks up, anxious for news.
Has she been seen at that cafe?
Should we go there and see?
I’m looking into it, Mrs. Dixon. I’ll be in touch soon, okay?
Lynette sinks back in her chair, defeated.
Thank you, detective.
You’re very welcome. Take care.
Investigation: Day 8
The following is a text message conversation between Agent Falco and Deputy Decker, initiated June 27, 7:37 AM.
How’s the search going, Deputy?
Peachy, Agent Falco. Literally.
What does that mean?
A tube of peach lip gloss busted all over Libby’s sock drawer.
I guess she hadn’t noticed yet.
Have you found anything helpful, Deputy Decker?
I found a few rubbers hidden in a pair of socks.
Condoms?
So it does seem like Libby was sexually active…
But I need to know if she’s actually pregnant.
Could she have run off to get an abortion, you think?
Possibly — could be what the fake ID was for.
You have to be 18 to get an abortion without parental consent in Tennessee.
But she didn’t need to leave her car and cell phone behind for that.
Yeah.
Unless something went wrong, maybe?
What’s your theory, Deputy?
She acquires the fake ID to get the abortion.
She goes to the clinic, but they know it’s a fake.
The doctors there turn Libby away…
So she and Bronco have to take matters into their own hands.
Are you suggesting they tried to perform the abortion themselves, Decker?
Strangers things have happened, detective.
But say something DID go terribly wrong…
Libby’s death is accidental, but her boyfriend has to dispose of her body.
That’s what he does, and then he leaves her car and stuff behind.
Knifes the tire to make it look like a flat.
That way, it throws us off the scent — we think she’s been abducted off of Route 12 or something.
Okay, but where did this coat-hanger abortion occur?
There was no blood in Room 201 of The Junction.
Could be they decided to do it elsewhere.
I don’t really know.
But Libby was seen by the clerk at Wired, correct?
After she disappeared.
Yeah, but witnesses mistake IDs all the time.
Certainly — eyewitness testimony is notoriously unreliable.
It’s usually the worst kind of evidence.
But the clerk seemed so sure it was her.
He could’ve been wrong. I could ask him again.
Okay. Thanks.
So is Bronco now our prime suspect?
I guess so.
But I’m not ruling out Duke either.
How come?
Say he found out about Libby’s pregnancy.
Assuming she’s pregnant.
Yeah. He’s pissed because she dumped him for this Bronco fella.
He finds out about the baby — sends those texts calling her a slut.
Follows her to the motel.
Pulls her over on her way home.
Kills her.
And then dumps the body and stages the scene.
That’s also possible.
Or maybe Libby didn’t want to get an abortion—
Perhaps she felt pressured by Bronco.
A child would’ve been evidence of their illicit affair.
Bronco could’ve seen jail time for statutory rape.
So she changes her mind about the procedure and he kills her to hide the evidence of their relationship?
That’s pretty cold.
Like you said, stranger things have happened.
But what if the clerk at Wired really did see Libby?
Could she have run off to protect her unborn child?
So she’s hiding from Bronco then, right? Not Duke.
Maybe she’s hiding from both of them.
And she threatened you from the Internet cafe because she doesn’t want to be found.
Possibly. We should check out some nearby women’s shelters.
And talk to bus drivers and taxi cabs?
Yeah. She left her vehicle out on Route 12.
She had to get to the shelter somehow, if that’s where she went.
But could a scared, pregnant teen really pull something like that off?
Could she really vanish into thin air without any help or resources?
I don’t know.
But I found something under her pillow.
A copy of the mystery novel “Ghost Girl.”
Is that relevant, Deputy?
Page 68 is dog-eared.
That seems to be the page where the heroine disappears.
Excuse me?
“Ghost Girl” is about a teen who goes missing. Coincidence?
I don’t know.
It could be.
I guess it’s a pretty popular book — Cate has a copy.
It’s eerie, but let’s look for something a little more concrete.
What about Libby’s bedroom? Anything missing?
Is there any evidence that she packed her things?
Not that I can see.
Her stuffed pig’s still here.
Lynette doesn’t think she’d have left without Napoleon.
Napoleon? Like the pig from “Animal Farm?”
I don’t know. I haven’t read “Animal Farm.”
Keep looking around, Deputy.
I’m going to check out Scoops.
Sounds good. I’ll let you know if I find anything else.
Okay, thanks, Decker.
No problem, boss.
The following is an audio call from Jason Spelling, the clerk at Wired, to Agent Falco, placed June 27, 1:13 PM.
Falco.
Hi, Detective Falco. This is Jason Spelling from the Wired cafe. I talked to a deputy a few days ago, and he left your business card here—
Said I should call you if I saw that chick again.
Are you talking about Libby Dixon?
Yeah, I guess. That girl from the missing poster he showed me.
And you told Deputy Decker you’d seen her before, right?
Yeah, she’s been in a couple times.
I mean, she had giant sunglasses on, but I remember what she looks like.
So you’re calling to tell me she’s been in again?
Well, yeah, I mean — she’s here now. Same sunglasses, same big boobs.
She’s there right now?
Yeah, she’s on Terminal A3.
Describe her to me, Mr. Spelling.
Uh, she’s like medium-height, I guess. Tan skin. Totally stacked. She’s got brown hair—
I don’t know what color her eyes are ‘cause of the sunglasses.
What is she wearing, sir?
Jeans and a tee shirt. She’s got a sweater tied around her waist, prob’ly brought it ‘cause they blast the AC in here.
Is she with anyone? Have you seen her talking to anybody?
No, she’s here by herself.
She looks just like the girl on the poster. She’s definitely the chick I saw in here before.
Are you sure?
Totally. She acts all nervous when she’s here, like she’s tweaked out on caffeine or something…
But she never orders any coffee.
What do you mean, she’s acting nervous?
I don’t know — she just kinda seems on edge, you know?
Okay, I’m about half an hour out of Newbury. I need you to stall her if she tries to leave, all right?
Stall her? Like how?
Tell her there’s a problem with her payment or something.
You pay for your time block before you log on, detective.
Like, the terminal won’t let you get on the ‘net ‘til you insert cash or swipe your card.
Okay, well, chat her up, then.
Excuse me?
Talk to her, flirt with her — just act natural, okay?
Uh, okay.
Don’t tell her that you recognize her, got it?
Yeah, I got it.
I’m leaving right now. Thanks for your help, Mr. Spelling.
All right. See you soon.
The following is a communication from “Connor Mason” to Agent Falco on the Facespace messaging app, sent June 27, 1:20 PM.
You need to stop asking questions, bitch.
Let the Dixon case be.
Tell me who this is.
No.
Is this Libby?
No.
You won’t get in trouble, okay?
Your family just wants you home safe.
I told you I’m not Libby.
Okay. Then who are you?
Your worst nightmare.
I know where you sleep, lady.
You need to stop.
Is Libby okay?
Do you know where she is?
You’re not getting it, are you?
Tell me if she’s still alive.
Tell me your real name.
49 Union Street, Cedar Creek, TN, 37099.
Is that the address for The Winchester?
How do you know which hotel I’m staying at?
Have you been following me?
How are you connected to the Dixon case?
Hello?
Connor Mason is offline.
The following is a text message conversation between Agent Falco and Deputy Decker, initiated June 27, 1:52 PM.
I’m out at Wired, Decker.
But the girl we’re looking for isn’t here.
That’s some rotten luck.
The clerk said she left when he was in the bathroom.
So much for stalling her.
And nobody else here seems to have noticed much about her.
I’m headed back to Cedar Creek — we can talk more then.
I was just about to call you, actually.
You might want to stop off at Stark’s Quarry on your way back, detective.
It’s a few miles out of town.
Stark’s Quarry?
Why do I need to stop there?
That’s why I was about to call you.
A swimmer just contacted 911 from that location.
Okay. How come?
To tell us what he found out floating in the water—
The dead body of a young girl.
